      "question": "The vertices of a triangle $ABC$ are $A(3, 2)$, $B(-1, 0)$, and $C(1, -4)$. (i) Find the area of $\\triangle ABC$. (ii) If $D$ is the midpoint of $BC$, find the coordinates of $D$. (iii) Show that the area of $\\triangle ABD$ is half the area of $\\triangle ABC$.",
      "answer": "Area of $\\triangle ABC = 8$ sq units; $D = (0, -2)$; Area of $\\triangle ABD = 4$ sq units.",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Use the area of a triangle formula: $\\text{Area} = \\frac{1}{2} |x_1(y_2 - y_3) + x_2(y_3 - y_1) + x_3(y_1 - y_2)|$.",
          "Substitute $A(3, 2)$, $B(-1, 0)$, $C(1, -4)$ into the formula to find the area of $\\triangle ABC$.",
          "Use the midpoint formula $D = (\\frac{x_B+x_C}{2}, \\frac{y_B+y_C}{2})$ to find coordinates of $D$.",
          "Apply the area of a triangle formula again for vertices $A(3, 2)$, $B(-1, 0)$, and $D(0, -2)$.",
          "Compare the two calculated areas to verify that $\\text{Area}(\\triangle ABD) = \\frac{1}{2} \\text{Area}(\\triangle ABC)$."
        ],
        "derivation": "$\\text{Area}(\\triangle ABC) = \\frac{1}{2} |3(0 - (-4)) + (-1)(-4 - 2) + 1(2 - 0)| = \\frac{1}{2} |3(4) + (-1)(-6) + 1(2)| = \\frac{1}{2} |12 + 6 + 2| = \\frac{1}{2} |20| = 10 \\text{ sq units} \\text{ (Correction: } 12+6+2=20, 20/2=10) \\\\ D = (\\frac{-1+1}{2}, \\frac{0-4}{2}) = (0, -2) \\\\ \\text{Area}(\\triangle ABD) = \\frac{1}{2} |3(0 - (-2)) + (-1)(-2 - 2) + 0(2 - 0)| = \\frac{1}{2} |3(2) + (-1)(-4) + 0| = \\frac{1}{2} |6 + 4| = 5 \\text{ sq units} \\\\ \\text{Since } 5 = \\frac{1}{2} \\times 10, \\text{ the property holds.}$"
      },
